<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1402,2031]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,330,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name is a Latin adjective meaning slender or thin, and refers to the small size and fragile appearance of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1402,2031]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,317,1565,1591]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Santos" authorityName="Santos" box="[336,616,1565,1591]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[336,527,1566,1591]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Architis gracilis</emphasis>
Santos
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[627,724,1565,1591]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[627,724,1565,1591]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs from all the remaining species of the genus by the combination of a DTP which is not curved retrolaterally, a large conductor and the exposed portion of embolus which is long and bent apically (
<figureCitation box="[574,645,1645,1671]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1830,1854]" captionTargetBox="[269,1319,230,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[248,1350,197,1818]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Architis spp. 1 – 3, Architis gracilis Santos sp. nov. (holotype): 1, male habitus, dorsal view; 2, male pedipalpus, ventral view; 3, ditto, retrolateral view. 4 – 6, Architis catuaba Santos sp. nov. (holotype): 4, female carapace, dorsal view; 5, female epigynum, ventral view; 6, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; dRTA, dorsal branch of retrolateral tibial apophysis; DTP, distal tegular projection; E, embolus; FD, fertilisation ducts; HS, head of spermathecae; LL, lateral lobes of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; SS, stalk of spermathecae; ST, subtegulum; T, tegulum; VTA, ventral tibial apophysis. Scale bars: 1, 4 0.5 mm; 2 – 3, 5 – 6, 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182890/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[628,645,1645,1671]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1402,2031]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,152,378]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,421,1685,1711]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Description. Male</emphasis>
(based on 
<typeStatus box="[552,654,1685,1711]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">holotype</typeStatus>
from Senador Guiomard, 
<collectingCountry box="[967,1044,1685,1711]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">Brazil</collectingCountry>
). Carapace orange, with a pair of longitudinal black stripes. Anterior eye row slightly procurved, with eyes equally sized and smaller than posterior eyes (
<figureCitation box="[291,360,1765,1791]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1830,1854]" captionTargetBox="[269,1319,230,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[248,1350,197,1818]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Architis spp. 1 – 3, Architis gracilis Santos sp. nov. (holotype): 1, male habitus, dorsal view; 2, male pedipalpus, ventral view; 3, ditto, retrolateral view. 4 – 6, Architis catuaba Santos sp. nov. (holotype): 4, female carapace, dorsal view; 5, female epigynum, ventral view; 6, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; dRTA, dorsal branch of retrolateral tibial apophysis; DTP, distal tegular projection; E, embolus; FD, fertilisation ducts; HS, head of spermathecae; LL, lateral lobes of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; SS, stalk of spermathecae; ST, subtegulum; T, tegulum; VTA, ventral tibial apophysis. Scale bars: 1, 4 0.5 mm; 2 – 3, 5 – 6, 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182890/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[346,360,1765,1791]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Clypeus orange, chelicerae orange with a frontal median black spot. Labium, endites and sternum orange. Legs orange, darker from basal third of femur to apex of tarsus. Pedipalpus orange, with a black ventral spot on trochanter and a black prolateral spot on apical third of femur. Pedipalpal patella and tibia black on prolateral surface. Abdomen orange, gently suffused with dark-grey and with a black ring around the base of spinnerets. Spinnerets and anal tubercle black (
<figureCitation box="[924,992,1925,1951]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1830,1854]" captionTargetBox="[269,1319,230,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[248,1350,197,1818]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Architis spp. 1 – 3, Architis gracilis Santos sp. nov. (holotype): 1, male habitus, dorsal view; 2, male pedipalpus, ventral view; 3, ditto, retrolateral view. 4 – 6, Architis catuaba Santos sp. nov. (holotype): 4, female carapace, dorsal view; 5, female epigynum, ventral view; 6, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; dRTA, dorsal branch of retrolateral tibial apophysis; DTP, distal tegular projection; E, embolus; FD, fertilisation ducts; HS, head of spermathecae; LL, lateral lobes of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; SS, stalk of spermathecae; ST, subtegulum; T, tegulum; VTA, ventral tibial apophysis. Scale bars: 1, 4 0.5 mm; 2 – 3, 5 – 6, 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182890/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[978,992,1925,1951]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Total length 
<number box="[1165,1205,1925,1951]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.9">2.9</number>
. Carapace 
<number box="[1332,1369,1925,1951]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.1">1.1</number>
long, 1.0 wide. Tibia I length 
<number box="[442,481,1965,1991]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="2.3">2.3</number>
, II 2.0, III 
<number box="[616,655,1965,1991]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.7">1.7</number>
, IV 
<number box="[710,750,1965,1991]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.8">1.8</number>
. Abdomen 
<number box="[888,925,1965,1991]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="1.8">1.8</number>
long, 
<number box="[1002,1039,1965,1991]" pageId="1" pageNumber="52" value="0.7">0.7</number>
wide. Pedipalpal tibia as long as cymbium. Ventral tibial apophysis strongly bent retrolaterally and acuminated. Ventral branch of retrolateral tibial apophysis absent, dorsal branch well developed, concave ventrally. Distal area of cymbium long and narrow. Subtegulum visible in baso-prolateral corner of cymbium. Median apophysis well developed and rounded (
<figureCitation box="[262,370,232,258]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1830,1854]" captionTargetBox="[269,1319,230,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[248,1350,197,1818]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Architis spp. 1 – 3, Architis gracilis Santos sp. nov. (holotype): 1, male habitus, dorsal view; 2, male pedipalpus, ventral view; 3, ditto, retrolateral view. 4 – 6, Architis catuaba Santos sp. nov. (holotype): 4, female carapace, dorsal view; 5, female epigynum, ventral view; 6, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; dRTA, dorsal branch of retrolateral tibial apophysis; DTP, distal tegular projection; E, embolus; FD, fertilisation ducts; HS, head of spermathecae; LL, lateral lobes of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; SS, stalk of spermathecae; ST, subtegulum; T, tegulum; VTA, ventral tibial apophysis. Scale bars: 1, 4 0.5 mm; 2 – 3, 5 – 6, 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182890/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">
Figs 
<number box="[322,370,232,258]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,378]" box="[197,427,271,298]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,295,271,297]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,378]" box="[197,1425,311,338]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,388,311,337]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">Natural history</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[456,507,312,338]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">type</typeStatus>
specimen was collected by beating undergrowth foliage in a secondary forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[197,1142,351,378]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,378]" box="[197,1142,351,378]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,350,351,377]" pageId="2" pageNumber="53">Distribution</emphasis>
